[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi, I'm someone who's mainly been working with Coq and started dabbling in Lean recently. Currently I am facing the problem of wanting to unify dependent type arguments. Specifically assume I have the constructor <code>T (n : nat)</code> and want to show the equality of <code>T (a + (b + c))</code> and <code>T ((a + b) + c)</code> (see <a href=\"https://leanprover.github.io/live/latest/#code=inductive%20Test%20(n%20:%20nat)%0A%7C%20T%20:%20Test%0A%0Adef%20eqT%20%7Bn%20:%20nat%7D%20(t1%20:%20Test%20n)%20(t2%20:%20Test%20n)%20:=%20true.%0A%0Atheorem%20test%20(a%20b%20c%20:%20nat)%20:%20eqT%20(Test.T%20(a%20+%20(b%20+%20c)))%20(Test.T%20((a%20+%20b)%20+%20c))%20:=%20sorry\">this playground</a>). In the Coq world I could define a program lemma, where I could prove the equivalence of the dependent arguments for the types. How would I go about handling this in Lean 4?</p>",
        "id": 306565969,
        "sender_full_name": "verified_whale",
        "timestamp": 1666918421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can prove it via a rewrite but then the proof involves an axiom so is difficult to use. This is a real Achilles heel in lean and I had expected things to be the same in Coq. I have no idea what \"define a program lemma\" means and would be happy to hear more. In the liquid tensor experiment we usually don't attempt to use the resulting equalities, we define isomorphisms from T(x) to T(x') if x=x' and train the simplifier to cancel these isomorphisms when it can. Why do you need the equalities?</p>",
        "id": 306589744,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1666938250
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The way you state <code>test</code> surely cannot work in Coq either, with the exact kind of error you're getting in Lean. I don't know what a program lemma in Coq is, but an approach I have seen Coq people take quite a bit also translates to Lean just fine - e.g. Coq's Vector library defines a <code>cast</code> function and then states 'these kinds of theorems' in terms of it.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">inductive</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"bp\">|</span> <span class=\"n\">T</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">def</span> <span class=\"n\">eqT</span> <span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"o\">}</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">t1</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">t2</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"n\">true.</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Here we can use h to give proofs of equality for indices.</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">def</span> <span class=\"n\">Test.cast</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">m</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">â„•</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span> <span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">â„•</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">m</span> <span class=\"bp\">=</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">Test</span> <span class=\"n\">n</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"n\">eq.mpr</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">congr_arg</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"n\">h.symm</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"n\">x</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">--  add_assoc _ _ _ relates these specific indices.</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">theorem</span> <span class=\"n\">test</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span> <span class=\"n\">b</span> <span class=\"n\">c</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">nat</span><span class=\"o\">)</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">eqT</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Test.T</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">b</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">)))</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Test.cast</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Test.T</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">b</span> <span class=\"bp\">+</span> <span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"o\">))</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">add_assoc</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span> <span class=\"n\">_</span><span class=\"o\">))</span> <span class=\"o\">:=</span> <span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 306615097,
        "sender_full_name": "FrantiÅ¡ek SilvÃ¡Å¡i ðŸ¦‰",
        "timestamp": 1666949500
    },
